1 Structure of the statistical test

Inferential statistics is all about making decisions about the value of a particular observation or measurement. One of the most commonly used methods for making such decisions is to perform a hypothesis test. In this section, we will cover several statistical test to aid in data inference.

There are seven steps to follow when you are using any statistical test:

  1. State the null hypothesis \(H_{0}\) and alternative hypothesis \(H_{a}\)
  2. Decide the significance level, \(\alpha\)
  3. Compute the observed test statistics
  4. Determine the critical value
  5. Determine the p-value
  6. Determine the confidence interval
  7. Interpret your results


2 Hypothesis testing

Any hypothesis test starts with the formulation of the null hypothesis which typically suggests that there is no statistical difference between groups and the alternative hypothesis suggests that there is a difference. Suppose we have two different medicines, the first medicine is in group A and the other is group B. We denote the mean of group A medicine as \(\mu_{1}\) and the mean of group B medicine is denoted as \(\mu_{2}\).

To find out if the mean of group A is different from the mean of group B we construct a two-sided test as shown below:

\[H_{0}: \mu_{1}= \mu_{2} ~~~~~ (vs) ~~~~~ H_{a}:\mu_{1} \neq \mu_{2}\]

To find out if the mean of group A is greater than the mean of group B we construct a right-tailed test (or one-sided test) as shown below:

\[H_{0}: \mu_{1}= \mu_{2} ~~~~~ (vs) ~~~~~ H_{a}:\mu_{1} \ge \mu_{2}\]

To find out if the mean of group A is less than the mean of group B we construct a left-tailed test (or one-sided test) as shown below:

\[H_{0}: \mu_{1}= \mu_{2} ~~~~~ (vs) ~~~~~ H_{a}:\mu_{1} \le \mu_{2}\]

After formatting your hypothesis you need to decide the significance level yourself (typically set to 5% or 1%). A significance level is a probability of rejecting the null hypothesis when it is true and it is denoted by \(\alpha\). There are two approaches to make your decision of rejecting the null hypothesis. These are:

  • The critical value approach
  • The p-value approach

2.2 Critical Value approach

By applying the critical value approach it is determined whether or not the observed test statistic is more extreme than a defined critical value - the observed test statistic (calculated based on sample data) is compared to the critical value. The following three figures show a right-tailed test, a left tailed test, and a two-sided test. The figures represent an idealised model(not all models follow a normal probability curve, this one is considered ideal and useful to explain the theory).

For a right-tailed test, the null hypothesis is rejected when the observed test statistics value is greater than the critical value.


\[H_{0}: \mu_{1}= \mu_{2} ~~~~~ (vs) ~~~~~ H_{a}:\mu_{1} \ge \mu_{2}\]





For a left-tailed test, the null hypothesis is rejected when the observed test statistics value is lower than the critical value.


\[H_{0}: \mu_{1}= \mu_{2} ~~~~~ (vs) ~~~~~ H_{a}:\mu_{1} \le \mu_{2}\]





For a two-tailed test, the null hypothesis is rejected when the observed test statistics value is less than or greater than the critical values.


\[H_{0}: \mu_{1}= \mu_{2} ~~~~~ (vs) ~~~~~ H_{a}:\mu_{1} \neq \mu_{2}\]




Symmetrical distributions like the t and z distributions have two tails. Asymmetrical distributions like the F and chi-square distributions have only one tail. This means that analyses such as ANOVA and chi-square test do not have a “one-tailed vs. two-tailed” option, because the distributions they are based on have only one tail.

2.3 P-value Approach

A p-value is a probability of obtaining results as extreme as the observed results of a statistical hypothesis test, assuming that the null hypothesis is correct. The p-value is denoted as \(p\) and it is used as an alternative to the critical value approach. If \(p \le \alpha\) then we reject the null hypothesis and say the results are statistically significant. However, if \(p \ge \alpha\) we do not reject the null hypothesis and thus say the results are not statistically significant.


2.3.1 Quiz

Quiz

When are results not statistically significant?

  1. When we reject the null hypothesis
  2. When we do not reject the null hypothesis
  3. When we accept the alternative hypothesis


Using the p-value approach when do we reject the null hypothesis?

  1. When the p-value is less than or equal to significance level (\(p \le \alpha\))
  2. When the p-value is greater than or equal to significance level (\(p \ge \alpha\))
  3. When the p-value is not equal to the significance level (\(p \ne \alpha\))


Show Answer

When are results not statistically significant?

  1. When we don’t reject the null hypothesis (saying accept the alternative hypothesis is not considered as best practice)


Using the p-value approach when do we reject the null hypothesis?

  1. When the p-value is less than or equal to significance level (\(p \le \alpha\))


3 Statistical test

One and two-sample test can be carried out in Python. The one-sample test allows us to compare the sample mean/proportion to the mean/proportion of the population, or to a hypothesised value, to determine if they are significantly different. However, the two-sample test is used to determine whether two sample means/proportions of different groups vary. In this course, we will be considering a two-sample independent t-test and chi-square independence test only. The table below is meant to serve as a general guide when deciding which statistical test to run.


3.1 T-Test

A two-sample independent t-test is a statistical test to determine whether the mean values of two independent/unrelated groups are significantly different from one another when the population variance/standard deviation is unknown. The assumptions of the two-sample independent t-test are as follows:

  • The data are continuous and follow the normal probability distribution.
  • The variances of the two samples are equal (then Student’s independent t-test is used) and if the variance is unequal then (Welch’s independent t-test is used)
  • The two samples are independent (if they are not independent then we use paired t-test)
  • The sampling method for each group is simple random sampling.

We will be using the airquality dataset again to find out if the average temperature in June is significantly different from the average temperature in September. So, we will create two data frames that contains all observations in June and September respectively and then select the temperature column from both datasets as shown below:

# Here we are filtering airquality data to get two data frames 
# first consist of observations in June and second consist of observations in September

june = airquality[airquality['month'] == 6]

sep = airquality[airquality['month'] == 9]

# Then select the temperature column 

temp_june = june['temp']

temp_sep = sep['temp']

Step 1: Construct a two-tailed test where the null hypothesis and alternative hypothesis are shown below:

\(H_{0}:\) Mean temperature in June is the same as the mean temperature in September

\(H_{a}:\) Mean temperature in June is different from the mean temperature in September


Step 2: Choose your significance level \(\alpha=0.05\) (typically it is 5% or 1%)

# Assigning significance level to be 0.05 

alpha = 0.05

Step 3: Run two-sided t-test by running one function as shown below:

# Run two-sided independent t-test where x and y needs to be an array-like or float
# parameter paired = False means the groups are independent 
# parameter correction = auto means it will automatically use Welch t-test (variance unequal)
# our alpha is 0.05

t_test = pg.ttest(x=temp_june, y=temp_sep, paired=False, tail='two-sided',
                  correction='auto', confidence=0.95)

# Display the results
# by specifying the name of the variable 
# or using print() function if you are using spyder

t_test
##                T  dof       tail  ...  cohen-d   BF10    power
## T-test  1.131764   58  two-sided  ...  0.29222  0.449  0.19959
## 
## [1 rows x 8 columns]

Reminder: If you are using Jupyter Notebook or RStudio then you can print your output by specifying the variable name however if you are using Spyder then you need to use the print() function to print output.

The function returns:

  • T-value: the observed value of t statistics. We compare this observed value with the critical value to determine if there is a statistically significant difference between mean temperature in both months.

  • dof: the degrees of freedom of an estimate, it is the number of independent pieces of information that went into calculating the estimate. It is used to calculate the critical value.

  • p-value: the p-value of the test. If \(p \le \alpha\) then we reject the null hypothesis and say the results are statistically significant.

  • 95% confidence intervals: is the estimated range of values that is likely to include an unknown population parameter. If the confidence interval does not contain the null hypothesis value, the results are statistically significant.

  • cohen-d: the measure of effect size (we will cover this in the Hypothesis testing course)

  • power: it is the achieved power of the test (we will cover this in the Hypothesis testing course)

  • BF10: Bayes Factor of the alternative hypothesis


Step 4: Critical value approach: Determine the critical value to compare with the observed test statistics.

# Finding the critical value using ss package 
# for two-sided test our quantile is 1- alpha/2 where alpha is significance level
# it is a two-sided test that is why we divide it by 2 and then we specify the degrees of freedom (df)

t_critical = ss.t.ppf(q=1-alpha/2, df=58)

# Round the critical value to 3 decimal places
round(t_critical, 3)
## 2.002

The critical values are \(\pm t_{\alpha/2,58}=\pm 2.002\). So, any value above \(+2.002\) and below \(-2.002\) is inside the rejection region which means if the value of observed t statistics is above \(+2.002\) and/or below \(-2.002\), then we reject the null hypothesis at a 5% significance level. However, if the value of observed t statistics is outside this range then it is called a non-rejection region because we do not reject the null hypothesis. We can construct the non-rejection region as shown below:

# Constructing the Non-rejection region where any value above +2.002 
# and any value below -2.002 is considered to be in the non-rejection region
 
non_rejection_region = print("−", round(t_critical,3), round(t_critical,3)) 
## − 2.002 2.002
# Display the observed test statistic

t_test['T']
 
## T-test    1.131764
## Name: T, dtype: float64

The observed test statistic (t=1.132) is inside the non-rejection region. This suggests we cannot reject the null hypothesis at a 5% significance level.


Step 5: P-value approach

# Display the p-value 

t_test['p-val']
## T-test    0.262391
## Name: p-val, dtype: float64

The p-value is greater than \(\alpha=0.05\), so there is not enough evidence to reject the null hypothesis at a 5% significance level. This shows that the difference in mean of temperatures in June and September is not statistically significant.


Step 6: Determine the confidence interval

# Display the confidence interval 

t_test['CI95%']
## T-test    [-1.69, 6.09]
## Name: CI95%, dtype: object

The 95% confidence interval is (-1.69, 6.09) does include the null value, zero, hence the average difference in temperature between both months is not statistically significant.


Step 7: Interpret the results

Overall, we cannot reject the null hypothesis at a 5% significance level which suggests that the difference in mean of temperatures in June and September is not statistically significant.


3.2 Chi-square Independence Test

The Chi-square (\(\chi^2\)) independence test is an inferential method to determine whether two variables are independent/unrelated to each other. The null hypothesis is that the distribution of one variable is independent of the distribution of another variable, and therefore not affected by its presence. The (\(\chi^2\)) independence test compares the observed frequencies in a contingency table with the expected frequencies, given the null hypothesis is true. The data must meet the following assumptions:

  • There should be two categorical variables
  • Two or more categories (groups) for each variable.
  • Independence of observations. There is no relationship between the subjects in each group and the categorical variables are not “paired” in any way.
  • Relatively large sample size where expected frequencies for each cell are at least 1 and expected frequencies should be at least 5 for the majority (80%) of the cells.


We will be using the energy data to find out if the number of bedrooms and adults living in that house are independent.

First, we construct the hypothesis:

\(H_{0}:\) No association between the number of bedrooms and adults living in the house

\(H_{a}:\) There is an association between the number of bedrooms and adults living in the house

Usually, after constructing a hypothesis we derive a contingency table of one categorical variable against another: adults vs bedrooms. However in pingouin package, the function pingouin.chi2_independence() gives three main outputs: observed contingency table expected contingency table and the chi-square test summary.

# Using pingouin.chi2_independence get the expected, observed and stats

expected, observed, stats = pg.chi2_independence(data=energy, x='bedrooms', y='adults', 
                                                 correction=False)

## C:\Python36\lib\site-packages\pingouin\contingency.py:151: UserWarning: Low count on expected frequencies.

3.2.2 Chi-Square test after making corrections

We will now filter energy_data to remove very small values so that the chi-squared test works without any warnings.

# Remove the groups that are giving us problems so we select only bedrooms 4,5,6 
# then select adults 3,4 from those filtered bedrooms

filtered_bedrooms = energy[energy['bedrooms'].isin(['4','5','6'])] 

filtered_data = filtered_bedrooms[filtered_bedrooms['adults'].isin(['3','4'])]

Then, run the chi-squared test again as shown below:

# Using pingouin.chi2_independence get the expected, observed and stats

expected, observed, stats = pg.chi2_independence(data=filtered_data,
                            x='bedrooms', y='adults', correction=False)
                                                 
# Display the stats output

stats.round(3)
##                  test  lambda   chi2  dof   pval  cramer  power
## 0             pearson   1.000  1.470  2.0  0.480   0.071  0.176
## 1        cressie-read   0.667  1.469  2.0  0.480   0.071  0.175
## 2      log-likelihood   0.000  1.468  2.0  0.480   0.071  0.175
## 3       freeman-tukey  -0.500  1.468  2.0  0.480   0.071  0.175
## 4  mod-log-likelihood  -1.000  1.469  2.0  0.480   0.071  0.175
## 5              neyman  -2.000  1.471  2.0  0.479   0.071  0.176

The p-value is greater than \(\alpha=0.05\), so there is not enough evidence to reject the null hypothesis at a 5% significance level. This shows that there is no association between the number of bedrooms and adults living in the house. Since the chi-square test is one-tailed we can find the critical value from the scipy.stats package.

# Find the critical value, since,  it is a one-sided test so we don't need to divide by 2
# Then we specify the degrees of freedom (df)

ss.chi2.ppf(q=1-alpha, df=2)
## 5.991464547107979

Using theory from the one-sided test we can see the value of observed statistics (X-squared = 1.47) is much less than the critical value (5.99), hence the value for observed statistics falls into the non-rejection region, therefore, we do not reject the null hypothesis at a 5% significance level.
